Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["", "ManipulateCaptionSection"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In 1918, C. L. Fortescue stated his theorem: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["N", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " unbalanced phasors can be represented by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["N", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " systems of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["N", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " balanced phasors. Sequence components were created to facilitate \
calculations in unbalanced circuits and systems. Using the theory of \
symmetrical components, it is easier to analyze the problems of unbalanced \
systems (e.g. unbalanced load) and cases of faults in electric power systems \
(e.g. monophasic faults).\n\nAccording to [1], \"Fortescue defined a linear \
transformation from three-phase components to a new set of components called \
symmetrical components. The advantage of this transformation is that for \
balanced three-phase networks the equivalent circuit obtained for the \
symmetrical components, called sequence networks, are separated into three \
uncoupled networks. Furthermore, for unbalanced three-phase systems, the \
three sequence networks are connected only at the points of unbalance. As a \
result, sequence networks for many cases of unbalanced three-phase systems \
are relatively easy to analyze. The symmetrical component method is basically \
a modeling technique that permits systematic analysis and design of \
three-phase systems. Decoupling a detailed three-phase network into three \
simpler sequence networks reveals complicated phenomena in more simplistic \
terms. Sequence network results can then be superimposed to obtain \
three-phase results. The application of symmetrical components to \
unsymmetrical fault studies is indispensable.\"\n\nThe positive sequence \
consists of three phasors, one for each phase, with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"-", "120"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " degrees of angular displacement and equal magnitude. Thus, phase B is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"-", "120"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " degrees from phase A, and phase C is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"-", "120"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " degrees from phase B. A negative sequence is similar to the positive \
component, but instead of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"-", "120"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " degrees, the displacement is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"+", "120"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " degrees. The zero sequence is represented by three vectors of equal \
magnitude and equal angular displacement."
}], "ManipulateCaption",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.35696210375764*^9, {3.520173600453125*^9, 3.520173601203125*^9}, {
   3.52019380368334*^9, 3.5201938262811832`*^9}, 3.520193871029818*^9, {
   3.520193905895336*^9, 3.520194085861354*^9}, {3.5201941945748587`*^9, 
   3.520194438683325*^9}, {3.520194790962471*^9, 3.520194792750744*^9}, 
   3.52019794161036*^9, {3.5201980497810183`*^9, 3.520198109613172*^9}, {
   3.520852866132406*^9, 3.520852866412422*^9}},
 CellID->1468839793],

Cell["\<\
Here are the basic equations of the three-phase symmetric components:\
\>", "ManipulateCaption",
